[start section id="20112"]

I reviewed the patient's pathology, operative report, and colonoscopy.  I agree with Ms. Henderson's assessment.  This is a T3, N2, M0 carcinoma of the colon with 13 out of 45 lymph nodes positive.  I explained the significance of this to the patient and explained that, with stage 3 colon cancer, we would recommend adjuvant chemotherapy.  Standard chemotherapy oftentimes involves FOLFOX, but for people at the age of 77, consideration would be given to single-agent adjuvant capecitabine or 5-FU leucovorin only.  I described how the chemotherapy is given as an outpatient, intravenously, and talked about the side-effects of treatment with the patient.  His wife was present throughout all of this and took notes.  The patient is from Vermont and plans to return there.  I have recommended that they hook up with a local oncologist and arrange for treatments according to his status in about four to six-weeks.  I have given them my card so they know they can call me if they have any further questions.  The oncologist they select can also contact me if he so wishes.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn.  No apparent learning barriers were identified.  Learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

[end section id="20112"]

